DATA SOURCES AND ATTRIBUTIONS:

1. JPL Development Ephemerides (DE440, DE441, DE431)
   Source: NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory
   URL: https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/planets/eph_export.html
   License: Public Domain (US Government work)
   Note: JPL data used under public domain dedication

2. Russian Ephemerides of Planets and Moon (EPM2021)
   Source: Institute of Applied Astronomy, Russian Academy of Sciences
   URL: http://iaaras.ru/en/dept/ephemeris/epm/2021/
   License: Freely available for research and non-commercial use
   Note: EPM data used with attribution to IAA RAS

3. Swiss Ephemeris
   Source: Astrodienst AG
   URL: https://www.astro.com/swisseph/
   License: GNU GPL v2+ / Swiss Ephemeris Professional License
   Note: Swiss Ephemeris used under GPL v2 for non-commercial research

4. Project Pluto jpl_eph
   Source: Bill Gray (Project Pluto)
   URL: https://github.com/Bill-Gray/jpl_eph
   License: GNU GPL v2+
   Note: Used with attribution to Project Pluto

5. CALCEPH Library
   Source: IMCCE - Institut de Mécanique Céleste et de Calcul des Éphémérides
   URL: https://www.imcce.fr/recherche/equipes/asd/calceph/
   License: CeCILL v2.1 (GPL-compatible)
   Note: CALCEPH source code referenced but not redistributed

IMPORTANT NOTICES:

- This project is a research tool combining multiple ephemeris sources
- Commercial use requires verification of license compatibility
- Swiss Ephemeris commercial use requires separate license from Astrodienst
- JPL and EPM data carry no restrictions for scientific/research use
- Original source attributions must be preserved in derivative works

For commercial licensing questions:
